## Technical Correction
The original answer claims O(n log n) but block rotation in-place merge runs in O(n log² n): O(log n) merge passes × O(n) rotations per merge = O(n log² n).

## Corrected Implementation
```javascript
function sortInPlaceStable(arr) {
  const n = arr.length;
  let runSize = 1;

  while (runSize < n) {
    let left = 0;
    while (left < n) {
      const mid = Math.min(left + runSize - 1, n - 1);
      const right = Math.min(left + 2 * runSize - 1, n - 1);
      if (mid < right) mergeInPlace(arr, left, mid, right);
      left += 2 * runSize;
    }
    runSize *= 2;
  }
  return arr;
}

function mergeInPlace(arr, left, mid, right) {
  let i = left, j = mid + 1;
  while (i <= mid && j <= right) {
    if (arr[i] <= arr[j]) { i++; }
    else {
      rotateLeft(arr, i, j);
      mid++;
      j++;
    }
  }
}

function rotateLeft(arr, from, to) {
  const temp = arr[to];
  for (let k = to; k > from; k--) arr[k] = arr[k - 1];
  arr[from] = temp;
}
```

## Stability Analysis
Using `<=` (not `<`) ensures that when arr[i] == arr[j], we advance past the left element, taking it first. This preserves the original relative order of equal elements - the definition of stability.

## Cache Behavior
Bottom-up mergesort has excellent cache behavior: sequential access in both run detection and merging phases. Each pass processes contiguous memory blocks, maximizing cache line utilization. The rotation shifts elements within bounded ranges, staying cache-friendly.

## Space Complexity
Uses O(1) extra space - only temporary variables (runSize, left, mid, right, i, j, temp, k).
